    "refcode_long": "The Adventist Home, p. 404.3 (Ellen Gould White)",
    "element_type": "p",
    "element_subtype": "standard-indented",
    "content": "<strong>Satan Would Eclipse the Future Glories</strong>&mdash;Satan has worked continually to eclipse the glories of the future world and to attract the whole attention to the things of this life. He has striven so to arrange matters that our <span class=\"page-break\" data-page=\"405\"></span> thought, our anxiety, our labor might be so fully employed in temporal things that we should not see or realize the value of eternal realities. The world and its cares have too large a place, while Jesus and heavenly things have altogether too small a share in our thoughts and affections. We should conscientiously discharge all the duties of everyday life, but it is also essential that we should cultivate, above everything else, holy affection for our Lord Jesus Christ.<sup class=\"chapterendnote\"><a class=\"chapterendnote\">16<span class=\"chapterendnote\"><span class=\"egwlink egwlink_book\" title=\"RH 1-7-1890\" data-link=\"821.10146\">The Review and Herald, January 7, 1890</span>.</span></a></sup>",
